## Demo Flow -- Section by Section

### Pre-Demo Checklist (30 min before)

- [ ] Log into CS Workspace: https://orgecbce8ef.crm.dynamics.com
- [ ] Verify "My Active Cases" view is showing -- Ferguson case visible
- [ ] Verify voice channel status is green (connected)
- [ ] Verify Copilot panel is enabled (right side)
- [ ] Open portal in a separate browser tab: https://zurnelkaycustomercare.powerappsportals.com
- [ ] Sign into portal as `derek.lawson` (Scenario A) or `rachel.chen` (Scenario B)
- [ ] Confirm portal contact name appears in header/profile menu
- [ ] Open one existing case from portal to validate contact visibility
- [ ] Have second phone ready for simulated Mike Reynolds call
- [ ] Have this guide open on second monitor
- [ ] Quick test: open Ferguson account -> confirm revenue, tier, orders visible
- [ ] Quick test: open the phone case -> confirm timeline has notes, call, email

---

### Section 1: Connect & Orient (~10 min)

**No special data needed.** General workspace orientation.

**Navigation**: CS Workspace home -> point out left nav, session tabs, Copilot panel, multisession concept.

---

### Section 2: Their World Today (~5 min)

**No special data needed.** Validate their pain points, keep under 5 minutes.

---

### Section 3a: CS Workspace & Dashboards (~5 min)

**Navigation**: Home -> My Active Cases view

**What to look for**:
- Tier Level column with colored pills (Tier 1 red, Tier 2 orange, Tier 3 blue, Tier 4 gray)
- SLA timers on cases (countdown)
- Case origin icons (email, phone)
- Priority column

**Tip**: Ferguson cases should appear near the top due to Tier 1 + High priority.

---

### Section 3b: Email Case & Copilot (~10 min)

**Use any existing email-origin case.** Look for one that has an email activity on the timeline.

**Actions**:
1. Open an email-origin case
2. Show the auto-created case from inbound email
3. Open Copilot pane -> "Summarize this case"
4. Show suggested response draft

---

### Section 3c: Timeline & Customer 360 (~5 min)

**Use**: Open the Ferguson PO #94820 case (already open from a previous step, or navigate to it)

**Navigation**: Cases -> Search "Ferguson PO" -> Open case

**Timeline should show** (from Script 17):
- Internal note: "Prior discussion with Rachel Chen re: PO #94820" (Rachel mentioned scope reduction)
- Phone call: "Mike Reynolds - PO #94820 delivery timeline check" (March 3, 7 min, incoming)
- Email: "RE: PO #94820 - Q1 Hydration Products Order Confirmation" (Feb 20, Rachel's confirmation)
- Warehouse note: "PO #94820 warehouse status" (EZH2O staged, fountains/sinks backordered)

> **Demo gold**: Point out the warehouse note -- when Mike asks to cancel fountains and sinks, the agent can see those were backordered anyway. Cancelling avoids the backorder. This is the "aha" moment.

**Then click into Ferguson account**:
- Revenue $27.8B, 36K employees, Tier 1
- 3 open sales orders visible in related records
- Multiple contacts (Tom, Rachel, Mike)
- Case history shows previous resolved/active cases

**Talking point**: "Sales and Service share the same data. No integration to build."

---

### Section 3d: Knowledge in the Flow of Work (~5 min)

**Navigation**: From any case -> Copilot pane or KB search tab

**KB articles most likely to be suggested** (from the 30 in the system):
- "Order Modification Process" (if discussing PO changes)
- "Backflow Preventer Installation Guide" (if Zurn backflow cases)
- "EZH2O Bottle Filling Station Troubleshooting"
- "Warranty Claim Procedures"

**SOP articles** (surfaced automatically by the Intent Agent during phone/chat):
- "SOP: Processing Order Quantity Changes" -- surfaces when customer asks to modify order quantities
- "SOP: Expediting Urgent Orders" -- surfaces when customer asks to rush/expedite an order
- "SOP: Handling Invoice Correction Requests" -- surfaces for billing disputes
- "SOP: Tracking Shipments and Handling Delivery Exceptions" -- surfaces for delivery inquiries
- "SOP: Defective Batch Reporting and Quality Hold Process" -- surfaces for defect/recall scenarios

> **Presenter note**: Don't read these titles to the audience. Let the phone call and chat trigger them organically. When one appears on screen, pause and say: "See that? The system heard the customer's request and surfaced the exact procedure."

**Action**: Type a question in Copilot about the case topic, show it surfacing KB content.

---

### Section 3e: Teams Embedded Chat (~3 min)

**Navigation**: From any case form -> Teams panel (right side or tab)

**Action**: Start a chat, show case context auto-populating, mention "Capture to Case" feature.

Already configured and working.

---

### Section 3f: PHONE CALL SCENARIO (~10-15 min) -- THE MAIN EVENT

> **This is the hero demo.** Mike Schmidt said telephony is non-negotiable. Go all-in.

#### Setup

1. Have the Ferguson PO #94820 case visible in your session
2. Second phone ready with the voice channel number
3. Copilot pane visible on right side

#### Call Phase 1: Ring & Screen Pop (0:00 - 0:30)

**Second phone**: Dial the voice channel number.

**On screen**:
- Incoming call banner/toast appears
- Accept the call
- **Screen pop shows**: Ferguson Enterprises, Mike Reynolds, Tier 1 Strategic (red), $27.8B revenue, 36K employees
- Recent cases and open orders visible

**Say to audience**: "Notice the system immediately identifies the caller and shows the full customer context -- no 'Can I get your account number?' needed."

#### Call Phase 2: Greeting (0:30 - 1:00)

**As Mike (second phone)**:

> "Hi, this is Mike Reynolds from Ferguson, calling from our Houston distribution center. I'm calling about PO number 94820 -- the hydration products order we placed for Q1."

**On screen**: Real-time transcript appearing, Copilot processing.

**Say to audience**: "The real-time transcript captures everything. Copilot is already analyzing context."

#### Call Phase 3: Cancellation Request (1:00 - 2:00)

**As Mike**:

> "The Fort Worth school district project just reduced their scope. We need to cancel two of the five line items -- the floor mount drinking fountains, that was 25 units of the EK-DF model -- and also cancel the 40 stainless steel sinks. Those two lines are no longer needed."

**On screen**: Transcript updating, Copilot may suggest "Order Modification Process" KB article.

> **INTENT AGENT MOMENT**: When Mike says "cancel two of the five line items," watch for the **SOP: Processing Order Quantity Changes** article to surface in the Copilot pane. Don't announce it immediately -- let it appear, then pause and say to the audience: "See what just happened? Mike said 'cancel two line items' and the system surfaced a step-by-step procedure. The associate didn't search for anything -- the system understood the intent and delivered the playbook." This is the first of two "aha" moments.

**Agent action**: Open the case (if not already open) -- show the timeline.

**Say to audience**: "Look at the timeline. There's a note from March 3 where Mike warned this might happen. And the warehouse note shows those two items were on backorder anyway -- **cancelling them actually helps our fulfillment**. The agent has all the context without asking."

> **THIS IS THE KEY MOMENT**: The warehouse note says fountains and sinks were backordered with ETA March 12. Cancelling avoids the backorder entirely. This demonstrates the power of the unified timeline.

#### Call Phase 4: Expedite Request (2:00 - 3:00)

**As Mike**:

> "But here's the thing -- the remaining three lines, the bottle filling stations, the wall mount coolers, and the replacement filters -- we actually need those sooner. Can you move the delivery up from March 15 to March 10? Our FM contractor is starting the national rollout early."

**On screen**: Transcript captures new delivery date.

> **INTENT AGENT MOMENT #2**: When Mike says "need those sooner" / "move the delivery up," watch for the **SOP: Expediting Urgent Orders** article to surface. Say to audience: "Notice it switched -- different request, different procedure. It's not matching on one keyword. It's tracking the conversation as it evolves and adapting what it recommends. This is what we mean by understanding service intent."

**Agent response** (to audience): "The agent can see from the warehouse note that EZH2O units (120) and coolers (60) are already staged and ready to ship. Filters are shipping from Erie. The expedite is feasible."

#### Call Phase 5: Discount Question (3:00 - 3:30)

**As Mike**:

> "One more thing -- Rachel Chen mentioned something about a filter discount that was just approved. 15 percent on bulk orders? Can you make sure that's applied to this PO as well?"

**Agent sees**: The discount details are in the case history (Ferguson's resolved case about EZH2O filter bulk discount: 15% on 500+ units).

**Say to audience**: "The agent doesn't have to go hunting. The discount approval is right there in the customer's history. Rachel negotiated 15% on filter orders over 500 units. This order has 200 filters -- so the agent knows to check whether Mike wants to increase the quantity to qualify."

> **Smart demo tip**: This creates a natural follow-up conversation point. The agent adds value by proactively flagging that 200 units is below the 500-unit threshold.

#### Call Phase 6: Wrap-Up (3:30 - 4:30)

**As Mike**:

> "That's everything. Can you send me a confirmation email once the changes are processed? My email is mike.reynolds@ferguson.com."

**Agent actions**:
- Update case notes with modification details
- End the call

**After hangup** (the money shot):
- Copilot auto-summarizes the call
- Summary includes: lines to cancel, expedite request, discount inquiry
- Copilot drafts a confirmation email to Mike

**Say to audience**: "After the call ends, Copilot generates a summary from the transcript and drafts the confirmation email. The agent just reviews and sends. No manual note-taking -- what used to take 5-10 minutes takes seconds."

#### Fallback: If Voice Channel Is Not Working

- Open the case directly and walk through the screen layout
- Show the timeline (notes, prior call, email)
- Explain what the screen pop would look like
- Show the Copilot pane and how KB suggestions work
- Still effective, just less dramatic

#### Fallback: If Copilot Is Slow

- Continue the conversation naturally
- Show the transcript manually
- Point out where suggestions would appear
- "In a live environment, Copilot responds in real time"

