#### 4d Quality Management

**Status**: ✅ Quality Management is fully configured and LIVE. Connection references set, all 6 QEA/KM flows active, QEA + KM agents published. **Manufacturing Service Quality Standard** criteria published with 6 sections, 21 AI-scored questions. Two evaluation plans published and active.

**Say**: "The last piece of the care leader's toolkit is Quality Management. This is where supervisors can score agent interactions against evaluation criteria -- think of it as your QA process, built into the platform."

##### Navigation: Show Live Criteria

**Show**: Navigate to **Customer Service admin center** → **Quality Management** (left nav) → **Evaluation criteria** → click **Manufacturing Service Quality Standard**

**Say** (as you open it): "We've built a criteria set called the Manufacturing Service Quality Standard. It has six weighted sections with 21 questions -- all tailored to your service model."

**Walk through the sections** (scroll, don't read every question):

| Section | Weight | Questions | Key Point to Mention |
|---------|--------|-----------|---------------------|
| Customer Identification & Account Handling | 15% | 3 | "Did the agent verify identity and recognize the customer's tier?" |
| Technical Accuracy & Product Knowledge | 25% | 4 | "Heaviest weight -- did the agent reference correct specs and recommend the right parts?" |
| Process Compliance & Escalation Handling | 20% | 4 | "Hot word detection -- Urgent, Recall, Safety, Legal -- did the agent escalate properly?" |
| Resolution Effectiveness | 20% | 4 | "Was the issue resolved on first contact? Was documentation thorough?" |
| Communication & Professionalism | 10% | 3 | "Tone, clarity, setting expectations" |
| Tool Adoption & Efficiency | 10% | 3 | "Did the agent use Copilot, KB, and AI tools? This rewards adoption." |

**Say**: "Every question has AI-response enabled. The Quality Management Agent reads the conversation transcript and case notes, then scores each question automatically. The supervisor only reviews the flagged ones."

##### Navigation: Show Evaluation Plans

**Show**: Go back to **Quality Management** → **Evaluation plans** → show both plans:

| Plan | Type | Frequency | Scope |
|------|------|-----------|-------|
| **Daily Case Quality Review** | Recurring | Daily | Cases -- evaluates all resolved cases each day |
| **Conversation Quality Review** | Trigger | On closed conversation | Conversations -- evaluates every closed chat/voice interaction |

**Say** (explain the vision): "There are two approaches here. First, manual evaluation -- a supervisor picks a conversation, scores it against criteria like greeting, resolution accuracy, compliance language. Second -- and this is where it gets powerful -- the Quality Management Agent. That's an AI agent that automatically scores every interaction against your criteria and flags the ones that need human review. So instead of randomly sampling 5% of calls, the system tells you which conversations deserve attention based on sentiment, compliance keywords, or resolution quality."

**Say** (connect to their world): "Lisa, think about your QA process today. How many calls does your team review per week? And how do you decide which ones to review? With the QM Agent, every interaction gets evaluated, and the supervisor's time goes to the conversations that actually need coaching -- not random sampling."

##### Navigation: Show Scored Evaluations (if simulation has run)

**Show**: If a simulation has been run, navigate to **Quality Management** → **Evaluation results** → open a scored evaluation. Walk through:
- The overall score (percentage)
- Per-section scores with the weight breakdown
- Click into a question to show the AI's selected answer and its rationale
- Point out where the AI referenced specific moments from the transcript

**Say**: "The AI read the entire conversation and scored each of the 21 questions. It shows its reasoning -- you can see exactly why it scored this way. The supervisor can agree, override, or add notes."

**Key differentiator**: "With Salesforce, quality management typically requires Einstein Conversation Insights as an add-on, plus a third-party QA tool for structured evaluations. Here it's native -- same data, same platform, same admin experience."

---

### Section 5: AI Agents (~10 min)

**Three built-in agents to reference** (show outcomes, not config):
1. **Intent Agent** -- already demonstrated during phone call and chat. This is the reveal moment.
2. **Case Management Agent** -- auto-follow-up on stale cases
3. **Knowledge Management Agent** -- identifies KB gaps, drafts articles

**Intent Agent is CONFIGURED.** 10 intents across 2 groups with prescriptive SOP articles. See the Intent Agent Reference Card above for the full mapping.

**Narrative approach for this section**: Don't open config screens. Instead, refer back to the phone call:
- "Remember when Mike said he needed to modify the order and the procedure appeared? That's the Intent Agent. It recognized the service intent -- not just a keyword match, but what the customer actually needs -- and delivered the right runbook."
- "We've configured it for your top 10 service scenarios -- the calls and chats your team handles every day: order changes, expedites, defect reports, quality holds, invoice disputes."
- "A new hire on day one gets the same procedural guidance that your 20-year veteran carries in their head. The system levels the playing field."

**For Case Management Agent**: "This one watches your queue. If a case sits for 48 hours waiting on a customer reply, it sends a follow-up. If a new case matches a pattern seen 50 times before, it can suggest the resolution. Think about your Tier 3 and Tier 4 volume."

**For Knowledge Management Agent**: "This agent watches for patterns. 15 cases about the same issue and no article? It drafts one and sends it for review. This is how you build that internal KB Benton wants -- automatically, from the cases your team is already resolving."

> **Do NOT**: List all 10 intents, show admin screens, or mention "2 groups" (that's our config language, not their value).

---

### Section 6: Platform Extensibility (~3 min)

**Just mention**: Power Apps, Power Automate, AppSource, code-first coming. Don't demo.

